data.sampled: The maximum potential loss (max loss) is calculated by subtracting the net credit received from the lowest possible outcome (strike price minus credit received). For example, if you sold a put with a strike price of $380 for a credit of $4.69, the max loss would be calculated as follows: max loss = $380 - ($4.69 + $6.93) = $27.31. Similarly, the maximum potential gain (max gain) is calculated by adding the net debit paid plus any dividends received to the highest possible outcome (strike price plus net debit paid). For example, if you bought a call with a strike price of $387.5 for a cost of $10.61, the max gain would be calculated as follows: max gain = ($10.61 + $6.93) + ($387.5 + $396) x $100/share = $52.59. Note that these calculations assume that the options will be held until their respective expirations and that there are no other investments or transactions involved.
